<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-034-229 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 442 910</DOCID><JOURNAL>CSN  Oct 14 1991 n531 p12(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Outsourcing stakes rise: hardware, software, nets now gettingfarmed out. (includes related article on outsourcing applicationsdevelopment)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Moore, John.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Outsourcing contracts are stretching beyond their traditionalboundaries of managing data center operations to include thepurchase of hardware, software and communications equipment.andP;  Onegood example of this is the pending contract between ComputerSciences Corp and General Dynamics Corp. That contract would haveComputer Sciences not only managing General Dynamic's three datacenters, but hundreds of engineering workstations and thousands ofmicrocomputers as well.andP;  The more comprehensive contracts are goodnews for large outsourcing companies, since they can supply suchdiversified service demands, but they exclude the smallercompanies or force them into the role of the subcontractor.andO;Analysts say that increasing corporate confidence in outsourcingis responsible for the broader contracts.andP;  One growing outsourcingservice is software applications development, which analyst SamAlbert says now accounts for 50 to 70 percent of IBM's outsourcingprojects.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     OutsourcingTrendsService CentersComputer ServicesMaintenance ContractsApplications Programming.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Contracts that go beyond data center outsourcing. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>